<!-- FAQ Section -->
<div class="faq-section" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Personal Injury Economic Analysis</h2>
<div class="faq-item" itemprop="mainEntity" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h4 itemprop="name">How quickly can a forensic economist provide damage calculations?</h4>
<div itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<p itemprop="text">We typically provide preliminary economic damage calculations within 3-5 business days of receiving basic case information. Full expert reports for personal injury cases generally require 2-3 weeks depending on complexity. Rush services are available for urgent cases.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item" itemprop="mainEntity" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h4 itemprop="name">What information does a forensic economist need to calculate lost earnings?</h4>
<div itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<p itemprop="text">To calculate economic damages, we need medical records detailing injuries and prognosis, employment records showing earnings history, tax returns for 3-5 years, education records, and work history. For vocational assessments, we also review functional capacity evaluations and transferable skills.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item" itemprop="mainEntity" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h4 itemprop="name">How do Rhode Island laws affect personal injury economic damage calculations?</h4>
<div itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<p itemprop="text">Rhode Island personal injury cases follow specific statutes including RI Gen. Laws ยง 10-7-1 for wrongful death claims. Our economic analysis complies with these requirements, calculating pecuniary losses, economic support, and household services while properly accounting for personal consumption offsets as required by Rhode Island law.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item" itemprop="mainEntity" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h4 itemprop="name">Can you review opposing expert economic damage calculations?</h4>
<div itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<p itemprop="text">Yes, we regularly provide rebuttal analyses of opposing economic experts' reports in personal injury cases. Our reviews identify methodological flaws, inappropriate assumptions, or calculation errors while clearly explaining why alternative approaches better reflect actual economic losses.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item" itemprop="mainEntity" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
<h4 itemprop="name">What makes a forensic economist's testimony admissible in court?</h4>
<div itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
<p itemprop="text">Admissible economic expert testimony must meet court reliability standards using reliable methodologies, peer-reviewed data sources, and accepted calculation methods. Our personal injury economic analyses use Bureau of Labor Statistics data, actuarial worklife tables, and established present value calculations that consistently meet admissibility requirements in Rhode Island and federal courts.</p>
</div>
</div>
